segments.text: Yeah, I think the Woodlands has done extraordinarily well in continuing to develop along the objectives that were set, not even in 1974 when it opened, but in the late 60s.
That's a long period of time to stay true to an ideal.
In fact, when HUD terminated, it had to do an environmental impact statement
that was required by law.
And one of the findings it had to make was whether the public interest would be protected or at least well served by that federal action of their getting out of the program.
And since they had invested public monies in the woodlands and the grants and whatnot that we talked about, they had to make a finding as to what
that the woodlands would continue to develop along the lines where, as opposed to the developer going off and abandoning the concept.
And it is a record in that environmental impact statement and the findings that I've made that the woodlands was going to continue.
The developer was committed to it, to the plan,

And that irrespective of the federal involvement, the Woodlands is going to continue to develop as it had set out to do, which coincidentally is the same thing that we're saying to the residents today in dealing with transition.
Just because we're going to create another association doesn't mean that we're going to change the pattern of development.
People are saying to us, we bought here, our biggest investment in our lives is the house.
We bought here.
because of what the Woodlands is.
And we don't want to see that change.
And we're saying, we're not changing that.
In fact, the reason that we're creating the other association is so that we can control the Development Standards Committee ourselves to make sure that we can continue to develop like this.
But anyway, HUD made that finding.
I think over time, there are going to be a lot of pressures on the Woodlands, which
might cause some people within the Development Corporation to question whether we should continue developing like this.
There have been pressures in the past.
And certainly the presence of Mr. Mitchell is going to make sure that we don't deviate from the straight and narrow, so to speak.
But I think over time, since this is a long-term project, there will be pressures if Mr. Mitchell retires and other people come to the helm.
In my mind, as an employee and as a resident, you've got to wonder if the next person sitting in his seat will have the same commitment
to the ideal that he has.
I hope that person does.
We are a unique project, certainly in this part of the country and one of only several in the nation.
We have shown that it can be done and can be done profitably.
I know one of
Mr. Mitchell's objectives in going into this program was to be a demonstration project and hope that others would emulate what we're doing.
I think we have influenced other developments in the Houston area to be done on a master plan basis.
But the future for all of us is uncertain.
I think that a public company needs to look at bottom-line profit.
There's always pressure to do that, and building these kinds of projects is not the most profitable type of real estate development that one can go into.
There's an awful lot of overhead.
There's an awful lot of overhead.
There's a lot of front-end, a lot of capital costs that need to...
accounting terms be capitalized, and the realization of the profits on those is down the road.
So I think it will be a challenge for Mitchell Energy and Development over the years as to whether it wants to continue with this development.
All of us hope that it will, and hope that Mr. Mitchell's successors have the same commitment that he has.
That, to me, is, you know, I think we've done a splendid job to date, and I think we'll continue to do a good job.
But there's an uncertainty in my mind.
That's where it lays.
You don't perceive it.
One of the things I've picked up, or I think I have, is that there's a profound commitment among the executives we've talked to to the ideals that Mr. Mitchell espouses.
That's one of the reasons why I gather they're here.
Yeah, there isn't an executive in this company who couldn't be making more money someplace else, guaranteed.
But the combination of professional challenge and excitement from working on this kind of project, together with being able to live in this environment, is what keeps people here.
It's very fulfilling.
And as I say, depending on who succeeds Mr. Mitchell, I dearly hope that, I probably shouldn't be talking, Mitchell will probably outlast me, but he's that kind of guy.
But this is a long-term project, and realistically we have to anticipate that.
And I hope the corporate commitment is as profound as you say.
as it is embodied in the one man.
Certainly people who work for the Woodlands Corporation share that.
This is something completely aside.
Most of the Woodlands Corporation people we've talked to live here in the woodlands.
How prevalent is that with the energy company?
Do you know a percentage of the people over there across the street that live in the woodlands?
I don't know percentage-wise, but, and again, I don't know of too many people over there, but of the people that I know in energy, in corporate, virtually all of them .
So there is probably, I mean, it would seem to me a resident is going to be much more interested in the community.
Oh, yeah.
In fact, after fashion, I adopted a policy, an urgent policy for the community association board that the
CORPORATION APPOINTED PEOPLE HAD TO BE WOODLANDS RESIDENTS ALSO.
AND WHEN THAT HAPPENED, YOU'D BE SURPRISED AT THE DIFFERENT AWARENESS LEVELS AND SENSITIVITIES OF THE PEOPLE SERVING ON THAT BOARD.
THERE'S ONE GENTLEMAN WHO LIVED ON 1960 IN THE 1960 AREA FOR A LONG WHILE AND SERVED ON THE BOARD.
When he moved to the woodlands, he became radical.
I had to calm him down.
A residential perspective causes you to make different decisions.
But I would dare say a large percentage of the energy people.
living in the woodlands, most of the ones that I'm familiar with do.
Because it was obvious that may be one of the enduring strengths of the corporations, the fact that people have bought into the dream, the vision, whatever you want to call it, and they live it out.
Are you inadvertently, intimately involved in, say, recruitment of industry to the woodlands, or the job?
I know this is a matter of some concern, promoting new jobs, new opportunities.
Only tangentially.
If an industry is looking at coming to the woodlands, then because of my work with the county, if they're looking for tax abatement, I might get involved.

If they're very, they're almost always interested in education, and I'm the principal contact person with the school district and also serve on the board of the John Cooper School, the private school there.
So if education's important, I'll help put whatever package, that part of that package together.
And if they want tax abatement, then I'll introduce that notion to the community association.
to see if they want to get tax paid.
But I'm not out recruiting industry or anything like that.
I just thought you might get quickly looped into being where you are.
Which brings up another issue.
Were you involved in the efforts to bring University of Houston up here?
No, not really.
Oh, OK. Because of this kind of continuing issue, we chased around the block a couple of times, but never really got a tag on them.
No.
The gentleman who's most directly involved with that is David Gottlieb.
We're going to talk to him.
David was with the University of Houston.
They came to work for us about four years ago.
And he's been on both sides of that fence, so he might probe him on that.
